ictims sometimes co-author their own losses or injuries. Evaluating a number of controversial cases involving euthanasia, sadomasochism, date rape, battered wives, and "innocent" aggressors, Vera Bergelson builds a theoretical foundation for reform. Her approach to comparative criminal liability takes into account the actions of both the perpetrator and the victim and offers a unitary explanation for consent, self-defense, and provocation. This innovative book supplies a practical and coherent mechanism for evaluating the impact of a victim's conduct on a perpetrator's liability in a variety of circumstances, including those that are now artificially excluded from comparative analysis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aCriminal lawxPhilosophyxUnited States. 0aCriminal lawxPhilosophy. 0aCriminal liabilityxUnited States. 0aCriminal liabilityzUnited States. 0aVictims of crimesxLegal status, laws, etcxUnited States. 0aVictims of crimesxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aVictims of crimesxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 7aLAW / Criminal Law / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477243340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804772433423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804772433.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles